I'd love to support a hong Kong place, especially in a place that doesn't have too many. Maybe my expectations are too high, or maybe I just went at the wrong time, but the food here just didn't seem to cut it compared to West coast HK BBQ. The BBQ pork was small and tough, closing in the territory of jerky. The roast crispy pork wasn't crispy enough, and ended up actually being hard. Even the rice was a bit dry. Saving grace for them was the roast duck, it was meaty enough but they also gave me the neck piece. I don't mind at all but I'm sure there may be some people who might. If there were other choices, I might try them first to see how they compare. It just hit the spot at the time, but I don't think I'm dying to come back just yet.

My husband and I love roast duck and Asian cuisine. We found this place to have very authentic dishes, however we noticed discrepancies in customer service. Our portions are smaller when compared to other customers when we dine in, and our takeout orders are always sent with dry old rice. We REALLY love their roast duck and if we stand at the counter to watch the Chef chop we usually get the order correctly with no portion misssing (our solution to the duck issue) and we simply make our own rice at home (solution to the rice issue). The last time I went, a customer ahead of me got beautiful, fluffy, steaming white rice and mine was dry, hard, and cold. The first time my husband and I ordered (dining in) our bill was $23 and included rice. The second time we ordered the same dish, but got no rice. The third time we ordered the same dish again but this time as takeout, charged $2 more and no rice. When I questioned about the rice, I was charged $1, given more cold, hard, dry rice, and she complained that I was paying with a card and not cash. I believe this is intentional when they don’t want you to return. It’s sad and I can’t understand why our business isn’t wanted. We are always kind and polite.

It may not look like much from the outside, nor will it look appealing once you step in, but you'll begin to understand why people come to BBQ King House once you taste the food. The meats here are their specialty. From steamed chicken, to braised duck to roasted pork - you name it, they cook it and they cook it ever so well. The meat is tender and juicy, making every bite super flavorful. It has just the right amount of oil for taste that will not leave you feeling too heavy. Personally, I would recommend the soy sauce chicken and roasted pork.  One helpful tip, they only accept Visa or Mastercard if your purchase is above $15. So be prepared to pay a fee if you're placing a small order and happened to run out of cash.
